<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<methodology slug="plg-metrics">
  <metadata>
    <tier>pro</tier>
    <group>marketing</group>
    <domain>conversion-optimizer</domain>
    <summary>PLG metrics: activation rate, TTV, free-to-paid conversion, PQL scoring, NRR, and cohort analysis. Every metric needs a single owner and version-controlled definition.</summary>
    <tags>
      <tag>plg</tag>
      <tag>metrics</tag>
      <tag>activation</tag>
      <tag>conversion</tag>
      <tag>analytics</tag>
    </tags>
    <difficulty>intermediate</difficulty>
    <created>2026-04-28</created>
  </metadata>

  <content>
    <title>PLG Metrics and Tracking</title>

    <summary>A metrics methodology for Product-Led Growth: the full funnel from acquisition through expansion, including activation rate, time-to-value (TTV), free-to-paid conversion, Product-Qualified Lead (PQL) scoring, net revenue retention (NRR), and cohort analysis. Every metric must have a single owner, a machine-verifiable definition tied to a single event in a single table, and a "who acts and how" runbook line attached to each dashboard tile.</summary>

    <why>
      <p>Single-number product metrics hide the truth about PLG health. NRR above 100% can conceal logo churn; global TTV median hides SMB vs. Enterprise variance. PQL scores drift as the product evolves and misroute sales motion within 1-2 quarters if not recalibrated. Metric definitions that live only in dashboards (not version-controlled) diverge silently from the underlying events. Cohort analysis is the floor — every metric must be cohorted to be actionable.</p>
    </why>

    <when-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Standing up a PLG dashboard with activation, conversion, expansion, and retention metrics in one place</item>
        <item>Defining or refining the activation event ("aha moment") and time-to-value for a SaaS product</item>
        <item>Designing a PQL scoring model from product behavior signals</item>
        <item>Running cohort analysis for retention and free-to-paid conversion</item>
        <item>Quarterly PLG strategy review where freemium vs. trial model and gating thresholds are on the table</item>
      </list>
    </when-to-use>

    <when-not-to-use>
      <list>
        <item>Sales-led motions where the buyer never logs in before purchase — PLG metrics produce noise</item>
        <item>Pre-product-market-fit startups: vanity metrics dominate, PQL scoring overfits to a tiny sample</item>
        <item>Self-hosted or single-tenant deployments where event telemetry is not centralized</item>
        <item>Hardware or one-time-purchase products without recurring usage signals</item>
        <item>Regulated industries where logging granular user behavior requires consent gates that break funnel completeness</item>
      </list>
    </when-not-to-use>

    <section name="metric-ownership-rules">
      <rule>
        <statement>Assign one owner per metric. Define the activation event as ONE event, in ONE table, fired in ONE place.</statement>
        <rationale>Without an owner, metric definitions drift and the dashboard becomes folklore. Cross-source UNION aggregations for activation always break when schemas evolve. A single-source activation event is the prerequisite for reliable funnel analysis.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <rule>
        <statement>Keep the metric catalog version-controlled (dbt + Git). Pair every dashboard tile with a runbook line: "if this metric moves, who acts and how."</statement>
        <rationale>Dashboards that change metric definitions silently are net-negative — they create false confidence. Without a runbook, teams review the metric but take no action, which is the same as not measuring it.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="core-metrics-with-benchmarks">
      <list>
        <item>Sign-up to Activation: activated / signups — benchmark 40-60%.</item>
        <item>Free to Paid Conversion: paid / free users — benchmark 2-5% (freemium), 10-25% (trial).</item>
        <item>Time to Value (TTV): median time from signup to aha moment — target under 5 minutes.</item>
        <item>Natural Rate of Growth: (organic + viral) / total signups — target above 50%.</item>
        <item>PQL to Customer: customers / PQLs — benchmark 15-30%.</item>
        <item>Expansion MRR: expansion MRR / total MRR — target above 30%.</item>
        <item>Net Revenue Retention: (MRR + expansion - churn) / MRR — target above 120%.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="nrr-vs-gross-dollar-retention">
      <rule>
        <statement>Always track both NRR and gross dollar retention (GDR). Never report NRR alone.</statement>
        <rationale>NRR above 100% can conceal logo churn: expansion revenue from remaining accounts masks a shrinking customer base. GDR reveals the erosion that NRR hides.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="ttv-segmentation">
      <rule>
        <statement>Track TTV segmented by cohort, acquisition source, user segment (SMB vs Enterprise), and onboarding path — never as a single global median.</statement>
        <rationale>Global TTV median hides large variance between segments. An Enterprise-heavy cohort with 30-minute TTV and an SMB cohort with 2-minute TTV produce a misleading median that drives wrong optimization decisions.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="pql-scoring">
      <rule>
        <statement>Calibrate PQL score thresholds against actual close rates monthly. Adjust before sales workload drifts.</statement>
        <rationale>PQL scores drift as the product evolves. Weights that predicted conversion 2 quarters ago may now route the wrong users to sales, wasting sales capacity on low-intent users and missing high-intent users who changed behavior.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <list>
        <item>High-weight signals (3 pts each): 100+ actions/week; invited 5+ members; attempted gated feature.</item>
        <item>Medium-weight signals (2 pts each): 10+ hours/month; 3+ integrations connected; exported or shared data.</item>
        <item>Score thresholds: below 6 = nurture; 6-8 = automated upgrade prompt; 9+ = sales outreach.</item>
      </list>
      <rule>
        <statement>When an agent proposes PQL weights, require it to report sample size and confidence band. Reject proposals based on samples under 200 converters + 200 churned trials.</statement>
        <rationale>PQL weight proposals based on small samples overfit. An agent reporting weights without sample size and confidence is producing a plausible-but-unvalidated scoring model that will misroute sales motion.</rationale>
      </rule>
    </section>

    <section name="cohort-discipline">
      <rule>
        <statement>Cohort every metric. Minimum: M0, M1, M3, M6 retention columns per signup month.</statement>
        <rationale>Single-number metrics hide the truth. Cohort tables reveal whether recent cohorts are better or worse than historical ones, which is the leading indicator of product-market fit changes.</rationale>
      </rule>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cohort tables displayed in dashboards with no action attached per cohort.</description>
        <reason>Retention diagnosis without root-cause analysis and an assigned experiment is theater. Each underperforming cohort needs a hypothesis and a next sprint action, not just a colored cell.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="agent-gotchas">
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent proposes SQL aggregations on event tables without including a test query against a known sample.</description>
        <reason>LLMs produce plausible-but-wrong SQL: UNION over UNION ALL, missed deduplication on user_id, off-by-one in window functions. Always require the agent to output both the SQL and a validation query.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent summarizes cohort retention as "retention improved" when M3 dropped 2 percentage points.</description>
        <reason>LLMs rephrase directional changes to sound positive. Demand verbatim numbers in cohort summaries; no rounding, no rephrasing of direction.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Sending per-user event data (including emails, IPs, names) to an external LLM for analysis.</description>
        <reason>Per-user event data must be aggregated before sending to any external model. Sanitize PII before any LLM call that processes analytics data.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agent conflates "activation" with "onboarding completion" in cohort summaries.</description>
        <reason>Activation (reaching the aha moment) and onboarding completion (finishing the setup wizard) are different events with different causal relationships to retention. Confusion between them invalidates the analysis. Inject the glossary into every analytics prompt.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <section name="limitations-and-where-it-fails">
      <list>
        <item>Activation events get over-engineered — a 7-step "fully activated" definition is unmeasurable; teams ship and forget.</item>
        <item>PQL scores drift as the product evolves; stale weights misroute sales motion within 1-2 quarters.</item>
        <item>Cohort tables become showpieces — readable but no action attached. Retention diagnosis without root-cause is theater.</item>
        <item>TTV is reported as a global median; it hides huge variance across segments (SMB vs Enterprise, mobile vs web).</item>
        <item>NRR &gt; 100% covers up logo churn; tracking only NRR misses customer-base erosion.</item>
        <item>Tracking infra debt: events fire from frontend AND backend AND third-party tools, with no idempotent definition; metrics drift silently.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="agentic-workflow">
      <p>A Claude subagent is well-suited for: drafting the metric catalog (definitions + SQL), proposing PQL scoring weights from a sample of converted vs churned users, reading dashboard snapshots and producing weekly executive summaries with anomalies highlighted, and translating cohort tables into prioritized hypotheses. The agent should NOT silently change metric definitions in production warehouses — its role is proposal + draft, with a human approving DDL/DML changes.</p>

      <p>Recommended subagents: faion-sdd-executor-agent — model the metric catalog as an SDD spec (definitions, owners, SLAs, alert thresholds). nero-sdd-executor-agent — for NERO-internal product analytics tasks. A plg-analytics-agent (suggested) — sonnet for weekly summaries and PQL scoring proposals; opus for cohort diagnosis and pricing-strategy suggestions; haiku for DDL/SQL boilerplate and dashboard config. faion-growth-agent — owns hypothesis prioritization downstream of metrics.</p>

      <prompt purpose="Cohort diagnosis with experiment recommendations"><![CDATA[
Given the metric catalog <attached> and last 8 weeks of cohort retention
<csv>, identify the 3 worst-performing cohorts, the most likely root cause
per cohort, and a single experiment per cause to test next sprint. Output
as a table with hypothesis, target metric, and minimum detectable effect.
]]></prompt>

      <prompt purpose="PQL scoring proposal from sample data"><![CDATA[
PQL scoring proposal: from this sample of 200 paid converters and 200
churned trials <attached>, propose signal weights, score thresholds, and
expected sales workload. State assumptions; flag where sample is biased.
]]></prompt>
    </section>

    <section name="cli-tools-and-services">
      <list>
        <item>dbt — Define + test PLG metrics in the warehouse (https://docs.getdbt.com/)</item>
        <item>cube (Cube CLI) — Semantic layer for consistent metric definitions (https://cube.dev/)</item>
        <item>metricflow — dbt's semantic layer (https://docs.getdbt.com/docs/build/about-metricflow)</item>
        <item>posthog-cli — Query Posthog events / cohorts (https://posthog.com/docs/cli)</item>
        <item>bigquery / snow (Snowflake CLI) — Run metric SQL ad hoc</item>
        <item>evidence — Code-as-config BI for metric narratives (https://evidence.dev/)</item>
      </list>
      <list>
        <item>Amplitude: SaaS, Yes (API) — Strong cohorting, behavioral analysis</item>
        <item>Mixpanel: SaaS, Yes (API) — Funnel + cohort + JQL</item>
        <item>PostHog: OSS + SaaS, Yes (API) — Self-host option; event + session + feature flags</item>
        <item>Heap: SaaS, Yes (API) — Auto-capture; weaker custom event control</item>
        <item>Madkudu: SaaS, Yes (API) — Built-for-PQL scoring</item>
        <item>Pocus: SaaS, Yes (API) — Product-led sales workflow on top of warehouse</item>
        <item>ChartMogul: SaaS, Yes (API) — Subscription analytics, NRR/MRR</item>
        <item>Stripe: SaaS, Yes (API) — Source of truth for billing + expansion MRR</item>
        <item>dbt Cloud / Cube Cloud: SaaS, Yes (API) — Hosted semantic layer</item>
        <item>Metabase: OSS, Yes — Self-host BI for the dashboard view</item>
      </list>

      <example type="good" title="pql_score.py — signal-weighted PQL score scaffold">
        <code lang="python"><![CDATA[
# pql_score.py — signal-weighted PQL score from raw events.
# Run weekly; output to user_pql table for sales routing.
SIGNALS = {
    "weekly_actions_gte_100": (3, "high"),
    "invited_members_gte_5":  (3, "high"),
    "tried_gated_feature":    (3, "high"),
    "hours_in_product_gte_10":(2, "medium"),
    "integrations_gte_3":     (2, "medium"),
    "exported_or_shared":     (2, "medium"),
}
def score(user_events: dict) -> dict:
    total = sum(w for k, (w, _) in SIGNALS.items() if user_events.get(k))
    band = "nurture" if total < 6 else "self_serve" if total < 9 else "sales"
    return {"score": total, "band": band}
]]></code>
      </example>
    </section>

    <section name="best-practices">
      <list>
        <item>One owner per metric. Without an owner, definitions drift and the dashboard becomes folklore.</item>
        <item>Define the activation event as ONE event, in ONE table, fired in ONE place. Cross-source unions for activation always break.</item>
        <item>Cohort everything. Single-number metrics hide the truth; M0/M1/M3/M6 retention is the floor.</item>
        <item>Track both NRR and gross dollar retention (GDR). NRR-only conceals churn.</item>
        <item>Calibrate PQL thresholds against actual close rates monthly; adjust before sales workload drifts.</item>
        <item>Keep the metric catalog version-controlled (dbt + Git). Dashboards that change definitions silently are net-negative.</item>
        <item>Pair every dashboard tile with an "if this moves, who acts and how" runbook line.</item>
      </list>
    </section>

    <section name="ai-agent-gotchas-extended">
      <antipattern>
        <description>LLMs propose plausible-but-wrong SQL aggregations on event tables (UNION over UNION ALL, missed deduplication).</description>
        <reason>Always require the agent to output the SQL and a test query against a known sample.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>PQL weight proposals based on small samples overfit.</description>
        <reason>Force the agent to report sample size and confidence band. Reject proposals with sample under 200 converters + 200 churned trials.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Cohort summaries paraphrased by the agent often invert direction ("retention improved" when M3 dropped 2pp).</description>
        <reason>Demand verbatim numbers, no rounding, no directional paraphrase.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Anomaly detection without a baseline is hallucination.</description>
        <reason>Provide last 8 weeks of values as context for any "anomaly" claim.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Privacy: per-user event data sent to an external LLM without aggregation.</description>
        <reason>Per-user event data must be aggregated before sending to any external model. Sanitize emails, names, IPs.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Agents conflate "activation" with "onboarding completion".</description>
        <reason>Force a glossary into the prompt and reject if the agent uses the terms interchangeably.</reason>
      </antipattern>
      <antipattern>
        <description>Quarterly strategy outputs (freemium vs trial) shipped directly from agent recommendation.</description>
        <reason>These are decision-grade outputs. Never ship the agent's recommendation without a human PM/CFO review.</reason>
      </antipattern>
    </section>

    <templates>
      <template path="templates/pql-score.py" purpose="Signal-weighted PQL scoring function with band classification"/>
      <template path="templates/dashboard.md" purpose="Monthly PLG metrics dashboard template with acquisition/activation/monetization/expansion/retention sections"/>
    </templates>

